  "prompt": "How do you pronounce PostgreSQL?",
  "response": "\"PostgreSQL\" is pronounced in a couple of widely accepted ways. Here are the most common pronunciations:\n\n1. **\"Post-gres-cue-ell\"**  \n   - **Breakdown:**  \n     - **Post** as in \"post\" (like after)\n     - **gres** rhymes with \"dress\"\n     - **cue-ell** by saying each letter individually: \"C\", \"U\", \"E\", \"L\"\n   - **Phonetic:** /\u02c8po\u028ast\u02cc\u0261r\u025bs\u02cckju\u02d0\u02c8\u025bl/\n\n2. **\"Post-gres-sequel\"**  \n   - **Breakdown:**  \n     - **Post** as in \"post\" (like after)\n     - **gres** rhymes with \"dress\"\n     - **sequel** pronounced as the word \"sequel\"\n   - **Phonetic:** /\u02c8po\u028ast\u02cc\u0261r\u025bs\u02ccsi\u02d0kw\u0259l/\n\nAdditionally, many people simply refer to it as **\"Postgres\"**, pronounced **\"Post-gres\"** (/\u02c8po\u028ast\u02cc\u0261r\u025bs/). This shorter form is preferred by some members of the PostgreSQL community and is perfectly acceptable in most contexts.\n\n**Summary of Common Pronunciations:**\n- *Post-gres-cue-ell* (`Post-gres-QL`)\n- *Post-gres-sequel*\n- *Postgres* (`Post-gres`)\n\nRegardless of the pronunciation you choose, all are understood within the tech community to refer to the same powerful open-source relational database system.",
